\series bold 
Measuring Lengths and Significant Figures
\series default 
 
\layout Standard

We are interested in determining the number of significant figures in length
 measurements you might make.
 How is the number of significant figures determined? Suppose God could
 tell us that the "true" width of a certain car key in centimeters was:
\layout Standard

2.435789345646754456540123544332975774281245623...
 etc.
 
\layout Standard

If we were to measure the key width with a ruler that is lying around the
 lab, the precision of our measurement would be limited by the fact that
 the ruler only has lines marked on it every 0.1 cm.
 We could estimate to the nearest 1/100th of a centimeter how far the key
 edge is from the last mark.
 Thus, we might agree that the best estimate for the width of the key is
 2.44 cm.
 This means we have estimated the key width to three significant figures.
 
\layout Standard

If God announces that the width of a pair of sun glasses is 13.276554577876542677
87...
 cm, then upon direct measurement we might estimate the width to be 13.28
 or 13.27 or 13.26 cm.
 In this case the estimated width is four significant figures.
 Obviously, there is uncertainty about the "true" value of the right-most
 digit.
\layout Standard

The number of significant figures in a measurement is given by the number
 of digits from the most certain digit on the left of the number up to and
 including the first uncertain digit on the right.
 In reporting a number, all digits except the significant digits should
 be dropped.
 (See the discussion of significant figures in Appendix A.)
\layout Standard

Let's do some length measurements to find out what factors might influence
 the number of significant figures in a measurement.
 
